# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pet-imaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The uptake of [18 F]FDG by tissues is a marker for the tissue uptake of glucose, which in turn is closely correlated with certain types of tissue metabolism.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] After [18 F]FDG is injected into a patient, a PET scanner can form two-dimensional or three-dimensional images of the distribution of [18 F]FDG within the body.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Since its development in 1976, [18 F]FDG has had a profound influence on research in the neurosciences.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The subsequent discovery in 1980 that [18 F]FDG accumulates in tumors underpins the evolution of PET as a major clinical tool in cancer diagnosis. [18 F]FDG is now the standard radiotracer used for PET neuroimaging and cancer patient management.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The images can be assessed by a nuclear medicine physician or radiologist to provide diagnoses of various medical conditions.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] In 1968, Josef Pacák, Zdeněk Točík, and Miloslav Černý at the Department of Organic Chemistry, Charles University, Czechoslovakia were the first to describe the synthesis of FDG.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Later, in the 1970s, Tatsuo Ido and Al Wolf at the Brookhaven National Laboratory were the first to describe the synthesis of FDG labeled with fluorine-18.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The compound was first administered to two human volunteers by Abass Alavi in August 1976 at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Brain images obtained with an ordinary (non-PET) nuclear scanner demonstrated the concentration of [18F]FDG in that organ (see history reference below).
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Beginning in August 1990, and continuing throughout 1991, a shortage of oxygen-18, a raw material for FDG, made it necessary to ration isotope supplies.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Israel's oxygen-18 facility had shut down due to the Gulf War, and the U.S. government had shut down its isotopes of carbon, oxygen and nitrogen facility at Los Alamos National Laboratory, leaving Isotec as the main supplier.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] [18F]FDG was first synthesized via electrophilic fluorination with [18F]F2.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Subsequently, a "nucleophilic synthesis" was devised with the same radioisotope.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] As with all radioactive 18F-labeled radioligands, the fluorine-18 must be made initially as the fluoride anion in a cyclotron.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Synthesis of complete [18F]FDG radioactive tracer begins with synthesis of the unattached fluoride radiotracer, since cyclotron bombardment destroys organic molecules of the type usually used for ligands, and in particular, would destroy glucose.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] This produces "carrier-free" dissolved [18F]fluoride ([18F]F−) ions in the water.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The 109.8-minute half-life of fluorine-18 makes rapid and automated chemistry necessary after this point.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Anhydrous fluoride salts, which are easier to handle than fluorine gas, can be produced in a cyclotron.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] To achieve this chemistry, the [18F]F− is separated from the aqueous solvent by trapping it on an ion-exchange column, and eluted with an acetonitrile solution of 2,2,2-cryptand and potassium carbonate.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The nucleophilic fluoride anion is basic, so anhydrous conditions are required to avoid competing reactions involving hydroxide, which is also a good nucleophile.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The use of the cryptand to sequester the potassium ions avoids ion-pairing between free potassium and fluoride ions, rendering the fluoride anion more reactive.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Intermediate **2** is treated with the protected mannose triflate (**1**); the fluoride anion displaces the triflate leaving group in an SN2 reaction, giving the protected fluorinated deoxyglucose (**3**).
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] [18F]FDG, as a glucose analog, is taken up by high-glucose-using cells such as brain, brown adipocytes, kidney, and cancer cells, where phosphorylation prevents the glucose from being released again from the cell, once it has been absorbed.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The 2-hydroxyl group (–OH) in normal glucose is needed for further glycolysis (metabolism of glucose by splitting it), but [18F]FDG is missing this 2-hydroxyl.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Thus, in common with its sister molecule 2-deoxy-D-glucose, FDG cannot be further metabolized in cells.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The [18F]FDG-6-phosphate formed when [18F]FDG enters the cell cannot exit the cell before radioactive decay.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] As a result, the distribution of [18F]FDG is a good reflection of the distribution of glucose uptake and phosphorylation by cells in the body.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The fluorine in [18F]FDG decays radioactively via beta-decay to 18O−.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] After picking up a proton H+ from a hydronium ion in its aqueous environment, the molecule becomes glucose-6-phosphate labeled with harmless nonradioactive "heavy oxygen" in the hydroxyl at the C-2 position.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The new presence of a 2-hydroxyl now allows it to be metabolized normally in the same way as ordinary glucose, producing non-radioactive end-products.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Although in theory all [18F]FDG is metabolized as above with a radioactivity elimination half-life of 110 minutes (the same as that of fluorine-18), clinical studies have shown that the radioactivity of [18F]FDG partitions into two major fractions.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Another fraction of [18F]FDG, representing about 20% of the total fluorine-18 activity of an injection, is excreted renally by two hours after a dose of [18F]FDG, with a rapid half-life of about 16 minutes (this portion makes the renal-collecting system and bladder prominent in a normal PET scan).
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] This short biological half-life indicates that this 20% portion of the total fluorine-18 tracer activity is eliminated renally much more quickly than the isotope itself can decay.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Unlike normal glucose, FDG is not fully reabsorbed by the kidney.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Because of this rapidly excreted urine 18F, the urine of a patient undergoing a PET scan may therefore be especially radioactive for several hours after administration of the isotope.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] All radioactivity of [18F]FDG, both the 20% which is rapidly excreted in the first several hours of urine which is made after the exam, and the 80% which remains in the patient, decays with a half-life of 110 minutes (just under two hours).
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Thus, within 24 hours (13 half-lives after the injection), the radioactivity in the patient and in any initially voided urine which may have contaminated bedding or objects after the PET exam will have decayed to 2−13 = 1⁄8192 of the initial radioactivity of the dose.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] In practice, patients who have been injected with [18F]FDG are told to avoid the close vicinity of especially radiation-sensitive persons, such as infants, children and pregnant women, for at least 12 hours (7 half-lives, or decay to 1⁄128 the initial radioactive dose).
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Alliance Medical and Siemens Healthcare are the only producers in the United Kingdom.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] A dose of FDG in England costs about £130.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] In Northern Ireland, where there is a single supplier, doses cost up to £450.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] IBA Molecular North America and Zevacor Molecular, both of which are owned by Illinois Health and Science (IBAM having been purchased as of 1 August 2015), Siemens' PETNET Solutions (a subsidiary of Siemens Healthcare), and Cardinal Health are producers in the U.S.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] The labeled [18F]FDG compound has a relatively short shelf life which is determined largely by the physical decay of fluorine-18 with a half-life of 109.8 minutes, or slightly less than two hours.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Still, this half-life is sufficiently long to allow shipping the compound to remote PET scanning facilities, in contrast to other medical radioisotopes like carbon-11 with a half-life of ~20 minutes.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Due to transport regulations for radioactive compounds, delivery is normally done by specially licensed road transport, but means of transport may also include dedicated small commercial jet services.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Transport by air allows expanding the distribution area around a [18F]FDG production site to deliver the compound to PET scanning centres within a 1–3-hour flight time.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Recently, on-site cyclotrons with integral shielding and portable chemistry stations for making [18F]FDG have accompanied PET scanners to remote hospitals.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] This technology holds some promise in the future, for replacing some of the scramble to transport [18F]FDG from site of manufacture to site of use.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] In PET imaging, [18F]FDG is primarily used for imaging tumors in oncology, where a static [18F]FDG PET scan is performed and the tumor [18F]FDG uptake is analyzed in terms of Standardized Uptake Value (SUV).
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] FDG PET/CT can be used for the assessment of glucose metabolism in the heart and the brain. [18F]FDG is taken up by cells, and subsequently phosphorylated by hexokinase (whose mitochondrial form is greatly elevated in rapidly growing malignant tumours).
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Phosphorylated [18F]FDG cannot be further metabolised and is thus retained by tissues with high metabolic activity, such as most types of malignant tumours.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] As a result, FDG-PET can be used for diagnosis, staging, and monitoring treatment of cancers, particularly in Hodgkin's disease, non-Hodgkin lymphoma, colorectal cancer, breast cancer, melanoma, and lung cancer.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] It has also been approved for use in diagnosing Alzheimer's disease.
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] (This is a problem for some diabetics; usually PET scanning centers will not administer the isotope to patients with blood glucose levels over about 180 mg/dL = 10 mmol/L, and such patients must be rescheduled).
[src:pet-imaging/fluorodeoxyglucose-18f] Then, the patient is placed in the PET scanner for a series of one or more scans which may take from 20 minutes to as long as an hour (often, only about one-quarter of the body length may be imaged at a time).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In nuclear medicine imaging, radiopharmaceuticals are taken internally, for example, through inhalation, intravenously, or orally.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Then, external detectors (gamma cameras) capture and form images from the radiation emitted by the radiopharmaceuticals.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] This process is unlike a diagnostic X-ray, where external radiation is passed through the body to form an image.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] There are several techniques of diagnostic nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Nuclear medicine tests differ from most other imaging modalities in that nuclear medicine scans primarily show the physiological function of the system being investigated as opposed to traditional anatomical imaging such as CT or MRI.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In addition, there are nuclear medicine studies that allow imaging of the whole body based on certain cellular receptors or functions.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Examples are whole body PET scans or PET/CT scans, gallium scans, indium white blood cell scans, MIBG and octreotide scans.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] While the ability of nuclear metabolism to image disease processes from differences in metabolism is unsurpassed, it is not unique.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Certain techniques such as fMRI image tissues (particularly cerebral tissues) by blood flow and thus show metabolism.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Also, contrast-enhancement techniques in both CT and MRI show regions of tissue that are handling pharmaceuticals differently, due to an inflammatory process.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Diagnostic tests in nuclear medicine exploit the way that the body handles substances differently when there is disease or pathology present.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The radionuclide introduced into the body is often chemically bound to a complex that acts characteristically within the body; this is commonly known as a tracer.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In the presence of disease, a tracer will often be distributed around the body and/or processed differently.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] For example, the ligand methylene-diphosphonate (MDP) can be preferentially taken up by bone.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] By chemically attaching technetium-99m to MDP, radioactivity can be transported and attached to bone via the hydroxyapatite for imaging.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Any increased physiological function, such as due to a fracture in the bone, will usually mean increased concentration of the tracer.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] This often results in the appearance of a "hot spot", which is a focal increase in radio accumulation or a general increase in radio accumulation throughout the physiological system.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Some disease processes result in the exclusion of a tracer, resulting in the appearance of a "cold spot".
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Many tracer complexes have been developed to image or treat many different organs, glands, and physiological processes.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Some of the most common clinical nuclear medicine procedures are: glucose metabolic imaging with F-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) for cancer, myocardial perfusion imaging for coronary artery disease, and skeletal imaging for both benign and malignant bone disease.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In some centers, the nuclear medicine scans can be superimposed, using software or hybrid cameras, on images from modalities such as CT or MRI to highlight the part of the body in which the radiopharmaceutical is concentrated.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] This practice is often referred to as image fusion or co-registration, for example SPECT/CT and PET/CT.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The fusion imaging technique in nuclear medicine provides information about the anatomy and function, which would otherwise be unavailable or would require a more invasive procedure or surgery.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Although the risks of low-level radiation exposures are not well understood, a cautious approach has been universally adopted that all human radiation exposures should be kept As Low As Reasonably Practicable, "ALARP".
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Working with the ALARP principle, before a patient is exposed for a nuclear medicine examination, the benefit of the examination must be identified.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] This needs to take into account the particular circumstances of the patient in question, where appropriate.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] For instance, if a patient is unlikely to be able to tolerate a sufficient amount of the procedure to achieve a diagnosis, then it would be inappropriate to proceed with injecting the patient with the radioactive tracer.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] When the benefit does justify the procedure, then the radiation exposure (the amount of radiation given to the patient) should also be kept "ALARP".
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] This means that the images produced in nuclear medicine should never be better than required for confident diagnosis.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Giving larger radiation exposures can reduce the noise in an image and make it more photographically appealing, but if the clinical question can be answered without this level of detail, then this is inappropriate.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] As a result, the radiation dose from nuclear medicine imaging varies greatly depending on the type of study.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The effective radiation dose can be lower than or comparable to or can far exceed the general day-to-day environmental annual background radiation dose.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Likewise, it can also be less than, in the range of, or higher than the radiation dose from an abdomen/pelvis CT scan.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Some nuclear medicine procedures require special patient preparation before the study to obtain the most accurate result.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Pre-imaging preparations may include dietary preparation or the withholding of certain medications.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Patients are encouraged to consult with the nuclear medicine department prior to a scan.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The result of the nuclear medicine imaging process is a dataset comprising one or more images.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In multi-image datasets the array of images may represent a time sequence (i.e. cine or movie) often called a "dynamic" dataset, a cardiac gated time sequence, or a spatial sequence where the gamma-camera is moved relative to the patient.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] SPECT (single photon emission computed tomography) is the process by which images acquired from a rotating gamma-camera are reconstructed to produce an image of a "slice" through the patient at a particular position.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] A collection of parallel slices form a slice-stack, a three-dimensional representation of the distribution of radionuclide in the patient.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The nuclear medicine computer may require millions of lines of source code to provide quantitative analysis packages for each of the specific imaging techniques available in nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Time sequences can be further analysed using kinetic models such as multi-compartment models or a Patlak plot.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Radionuclide therapy can be used to treat conditions such as hyperthyroidism, thyroid cancer, skin cancer and blood disorders.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In nuclear medicine therapy, the radiation treatment dose is administered internally (e.g. intravenous or oral routes) or externally direct above the area to treat in form of a compound (e.g. in case of skin cancer).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The radiopharmaceuticals used in nuclear medicine therapy emit ionizing radiation that travels only a short distance, thereby minimizing unwanted side effects and damage to noninvolved organs or nearby structures.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Most nuclear medicine therapies can be performed as outpatient procedures since there are few side effects from the treatment and the radiation exposure to the general public can be kept within a safe limit.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In some centers the nuclear medicine department may also use implanted capsules of isotopes (brachytherapy) to treat cancer.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] to form a stack of cross-sectional, tomographic images.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] (the anti-matter equivalent of an electron) when they decay.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The positrons travel a short distance in tissue and then annihilate with an electron giving off two nearly back-to-back gamma rays.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Positron emission tomography takes advantage of these back-to-back gamma rays to localize the distribution of the radioisotopes.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The advantage of nuclear medicine is that it provides molecular and physiologic information, but it is relatively poor at providing anatomic information and the resolution is relatively poor.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In recent years, instruments have been developed which allow both radioisotope and anatomic imaging.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Most widespread are PET/CT scanners combining PET and computed tomography.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Increasingly common are SPECT/CT scanners.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Instruments combining PET with magnetic resonance, PET/MRI, are starting to be used.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The history of nuclear medicine contains contributions from scientists across different disciplines in physics, chemistry, engineering, and medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The multidisciplinary nature of nuclear medicine makes it difficult for medical historians to determine the birthdate of nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] This can probably be best placed between the discovery of artificial radioactivity in 1934 and the production of radionuclides by Oak Ridge National Laboratory for medicine-related use, in 1946.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In 1896, Henri Becquerel discovered radioactivity.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] It was only a little over a quarter of a century (1925) until the first radioactive tracer study in animals was performed by George de Hevesy, and the next year (1926) the first diagnostic tracer study in humans was performed by Herman Blumgart and Otto Yens.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Later on, John Lawrence made the first application in patients of an artificial radionuclide when he used phosphorus-32 to treat leukemia.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Many historians consider the discovery of artificially produced radionuclides by Frédéric Joliot-Curie and Irène Joliot-Curie in 1934 as the most significant milestone in nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In February 1934, they reported the first artificial production of radioactive material in the journal *Nature*, after discovering radioactivity in aluminum foil that was irradiated with a polonium preparation.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The history of nuclear medicine will not be complete without mentioning these early pioneers.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Nuclear medicine gained public recognition as a potential specialty when on May 11, 1946, an article in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) by Massachusetts General Hospital's Dr.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Saul Hertz and Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Dr.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Arthur Roberts, described the successful use of treating Graves' Disease with radioactive iodine (RAI) was published.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Additionally, Sam Seidlin brought further development in the field describing a successful treatment of a patient with thyroid cancer metastases using radioiodine (I-131).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] These articles are considered by many historians as the most important articles ever published in nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Although the earliest use of I-131 was devoted to therapy of thyroid cancer, its use was later expanded to include imaging of the thyroid gland, quantification of the thyroid function, and therapy for hyperthyroidism.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Among the many radionuclides that were discovered for medical-use, none were as important as the discovery and development of Technetium-99m.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Segre as an artificial element to fill space number 43 in the Periodic Table.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The development of a generator system to produce Technetium-99m in the 1960s became a practical method for medical use.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Today, Technetium-99m is the most utilized element in nuclear medicine and is employed in a wide variety of nuclear medicine imaging studies.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Widespread clinical use of nuclear medicine began in the early 1950s, as knowledge expanded about radionuclides, detection of radioactivity, and using certain radionuclides to trace biochemical processes.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Benedict Cassen's work with a directional probe lead to the development of the first imaging with a rectilinear scanner.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Gordon Brownell developed the first positron scanner.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In the same decade (1954) the Society of Nuclear Medicine (SNM) was organized in Spokane, Washington (US), and (1958) Hal Anger developed the gamma scintillation camera, which could image a whole region at the same time.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Anger's scintillation camera (Anger camera) broadened the young discipline of nuclear medicine into a full-fledged medical imaging specialty.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Some of the earliest applications of radioisotopes were therapy of hematologic malignancies and therapy of both benign and malignant thyroid disease.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In the 1950s radioimmunoassay was developed by Solomon Berson and Rosalyn Yalow.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Yalow was co-winner of the 1977 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (Dr.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Berson had already died so was not eligible).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Radioimmunoassay was used extensively in clinical medicine but more recently has been largely replaced by non-radioactive methods.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] By the early 1960s, in southern Scandinavia, Niels A.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Later versions would have 254 scintillators so a two-dimensional image could be produced on a color monitor.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] It allowed them to construct images reflecting brain activation from speaking, reading, visual or auditory perception and voluntary movement.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The technique was also used to investigate, e.g., imagined sequential movements, mental calculation and mental spatial navigation.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] By the 1970s most organs of the body could be visualized using nuclear medicine procedures.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In 1971, American Medical Association officially recognized nuclear medicine as a medical specialty.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In 1972, the American Board of Nuclear Medicine was established, and in 1974, the American Osteopathic Board of Nuclear Medicine was established, cementing nuclear medicine as a stand-alone medical specialty.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In the 1980s, radiopharmaceuticals were designed for use in diagnosis of heart disease.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The development of single photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), around the same time, led to three-dimensional reconstruction of the heart and establishment of the field of nuclear cardiology.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] More recent developments in nuclear medicine include the invention of the first positron emission tomography scanner (PET).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The concept of emission and transmission tomography, later developed into single photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), was introduced by David E.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Their work led to the design and construction of several tomographic instruments at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Tomographic imaging techniques were further developed at the Washington University School of Medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] These innovations led to fusion imaging with SPECT and CT by Bruce Hasegawa from University of California, San Francisco (UCSF), and the first PET/CT prototype by D.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Townsend from University of Pittsburgh in 1998.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] PET and PET/CT imaging experienced slower growth in its early years owing to the cost of the modality and the requirement for an on-site or nearby cyclotron.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] PET/CT imaging is now an integral part of oncology for diagnosis, staging and treatment monitoring.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] A fully integrated MRI/PET scanner is on the market from early 2011.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] 99mTc is normally supplied to hospitals through a radionuclide generator containing the parent radionuclide molybdenum-99.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] 99Mo is typically obtained as a fission product of 235U in nuclear reactors, however global supply shortages have led to the exploration of other methods of production.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] About a third of the world's supply, and most of Europe's supply, of medical isotopes is produced at the Petten nuclear reactor in the Netherlands.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Another third of the world's supply, and most of North America's supply, was produced at the Chalk River Laboratories in Chalk River, Ontario, Canada until its permanent shutdown in 2018.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The most commonly used radioisotope in PET, 18F, is not produced in a nuclear reactor, but rather in a circular accelerator called a cyclotron.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The cyclotron is used to accelerate protons to bombard the stable heavy isotope of oxygen 18O.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The 18O constitutes about 0.20% of ordinary oxygen (mostly oxygen-16), from which it is extracted.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The 18F is then typically used to make FDG.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] A typical nuclear medicine study involves administration of a radionuclide into the body by intravenous injection in liquid or aggregate form, ingestion while combined with food, inhalation as a gas or aerosol, or rarely, injection of a radionuclide that has undergone micro-encapsulation.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Some studies require the labeling of a patient's own blood cells with a radionuclide (leukocyte scintigraphy and red blood cell scintigraphy).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Most diagnostic radionuclides emit gamma rays either directly from their decay or indirectly through electron–positron annihilation, while the cell-damaging properties of beta particles are used in therapeutic applications.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The most commonly used intravenous radionuclides are technetium-99m, iodine-123, iodine-131, thallium-201, gallium-67, fluorine-18 fluorodeoxyglucose, and indium-111 labeled leukocytes.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The most commonly used gaseous/aerosol radionuclides are xenon-133, krypton-81m, (aerosolised) technetium-99m.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] A patient undergoing a nuclear medicine procedure will receive a radiation dose.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Under present international guidelines it is assumed that any radiation dose, however small, presents a risk.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The radiation dose delivered to a patient in a nuclear medicine investigation, though unproven, is generally accepted to present a very small risk of inducing cancer.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In this respect it is similar to the risk from X-ray investigations except that the dose is delivered internally rather than from an external source such as an X-ray machine, and dosage amounts are typically significantly higher than those of X-rays.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The radiation dose from a nuclear medicine investigation is expressed as an effective dose with units of sieverts (usually given in millisieverts, mSv).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The effective dose resulting from an investigation is influenced by the amount of radioactivity administered in megabecquerels (MBq), the physical properties of the radiopharmaceutical used, its distribution in the body and its rate of clearance from the body.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Effective doses can range from 6 μSv (0.006 mSv) for a 3 MBq chromium-51 EDTA measurement of glomerular filtration rate to 11.2 mSv (11,200 μSv) for an 80 MBq thallium-201 myocardial imaging procedure.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The common bone scan with 600 MBq of technetium-99m MDP has an effective dose of approximately 2.9 mSv (2,900 μSv).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The rad and rem are essentially equivalent for almost all nuclear medicine procedures, and only alpha radiation will produce a higher Rem or Sv value, due to its much higher Relative Biological Effectiveness (RBE).
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Alpha emitters are nowadays rarely used in nuclear medicine, but were used extensively before the advent of nuclear reactor and accelerator produced radionuclides.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The concepts involved in radiation exposure to humans are covered by the field of Health Physics; the development and practice of safe and effective nuclear medicinal techniques is a key focus of Medical Physics.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Different countries around the world maintain regulatory frameworks that are responsible for the management and use of radionuclides in different medical settings.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] For example, in the US, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) have guidelines in place for hospitals to follow.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] With the NRC, if radioactive materials aren't involved, like X-rays for example, they are not regulated by the agency and instead are regulated by the individual states.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] International organizations, such as the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), have regularly published different articles and guidelines for best practices in nuclear medicine as well as reporting on emerging technologies in nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Other factors that are considered in nuclear medicine include a patient's medical history as well as post-treatment management.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Groups like International Commission on Radiological Protection have published information on how to manage the release of patients from a hospital with unsealed radionuclides.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] A **nuclear medicine physician**, also known as a nuclear radiologist or simply nucleologist, is a medical specialist that uses tracers, usually radiopharmaceuticals, for diagnosis and therapy.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In the United States, nuclear medicine physicians are certified by the American Board of Nuclear Medicine and the American Osteopathic Board of Nuclear Medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Initial introduction of radioisotopes into medicine required individuals to acquire of a considerable background information which was foreign to their medical training.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Often a particular application drove the introduction of radioisotopes into a health care facility.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] As other applications developed the physician or group that had developed knowledge of and experience with radioisotopes usually provided the new service.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Consequently, the radioisotope service found homes in several established specialties – commonly in radiology due to an interest in imaging, in pathology (clinical pathology) due to an interest in radioimmunoassay, and in endocrinology due to the early application of 131I to thyroid disease.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Nuclear medicine became widespread and there was a need to develop a new specialty.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] In the United States, the American Board of Nuclear Medicine was formed in 1972.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] At that time, the specialty include all of the uses of radioisotopes in medicine – radioimmunoassay, diagnostic imaging, and therapy.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] As use of and experience with radioisotopes became more widespread in medicine, radioimmunoassay generally transferred from nuclear medicine to clinical pathology.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Today, nuclear medicine is based on the use of the tracer principle applied to diagnostic imaging and therapy.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] After completing medical school, a post-graduate clinical year is followed by three years of nuclear medicine residency.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] A common alternate path for physicians who have completed a radiology residency is a one-year residency in nuclear medicine, leading to sub-specialty certification by the American Board of Radiology.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] A less common path for physicians who have completed another residency is a two-year residency in nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Additionally, as is commonly required in medicine, continuing education is also a requirement to stay updated with research and new methods often requiring additional assessment such as that found at the IAEA.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Nuclear medicine procedures are performed by Nuclear Medicine Radiographers, who require extensive training both in underlying principles (physics, instrumentation) but also in the clinical applications.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Nursing support, especially in the hospital setting, is valuable, but may be shared with other services.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Nuclear medicine is a technology embedded specialty depending upon a large number of non-physician professional, including medical physicists, health physicists, radiobiologists, radiochemists, and radiopharmacists.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Residency trained nuclear medicine physicians have the most extensive training and highest level of certification, including all aspects of diagnosis and radionuclide therapy.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] However, current U.S. regulations do not prohibit other physicians from interpreting nuclear medicine studies and perform radionuclide therapy.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Radiologists who are not sub-specialty trained in the specialty, nonetheless often limit their practice to practicing nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Some cardiologists, especially non-invasive cardiologists, will interpret diagnostic cardiology studies including nuclear medicine studies.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Radiation oncologists perform all forms of radiation therapy, sometimes including radionuclide therapy.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] Some endocrinologists treat hyperthyroidism and thyroid cancer with 131I.
[src:pet-imaging/nuclear-medicine] The mix of physicians rendering nuclear medicine services varies both between different countries and within a single country.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET is a common imaging technique, a medical scintillography technique used in nuclear medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] A radiopharmaceutical—a radioisotope attached to a drug—is injected into the body as a tracer.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] When the radiopharmaceutical undergoes beta plus decay, a positron is emitted, and when the positron interacts with an ordinary electron, the two particles annihilate and two gamma rays are emitted in opposite directions.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] These gamma rays are detected by two gamma cameras to form a three-dimensional image.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET scanners can incorporate a computed tomography scanner (CT) and are known as PET–CT scanners.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET scan images can be reconstructed using a CT scan performed using one scanner during the same session.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] One of the disadvantages of a PET scanner is its high initial cost and ongoing operating costs.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET is both a medical and research tool used in pre-clinical and clinical settings.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] It is used heavily in the imaging of tumors and the search for metastases within the field of clinical oncology, and for the clinical diagnosis of certain diffuse brain diseases such as those causing various types of dementias.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET is valued as a research tool to learn and enhance knowledge of the normal human brain, heart function, and support drug development.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET is also used in pre-clinical studies using animals.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] It allows repeated investigations into the same subjects over time, where subjects can act as their own control and substantially reduces the numbers of animals required for a given study.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This approach allows research studies to reduce the sample size needed while increasing the statistical quality of its results.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Physiological processes result in anatomical changes within the body.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Because PET can detect biochemical activity and the expression of certain proteins, it can provide molecular-level information long before any anatomical alterations become visible.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET achieves this by using radiolabelled molecular probes, which are taken up at varying rates depending on the tissue.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Regional tracer uptake in different anatomical structures can then be visualized and approximately quantified based on the amount of injected positron-emitting tracer detected in the scan, via metrics like the standardized uptake value.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] It is possible to acquire PET images using a conventional dual-head gamma camera fitted with a coincidence detector.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The quality of gamma-camera PET imaging is lower, and the scans take longer to acquire.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Alternative methods of medical imaging include single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), and ultrasound.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] SPECT is an imaging technique similar to PET that uses radioligands to detect molecules in the body.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET scanning with the radiotracer [18F]fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) is widely used in clinical oncology.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] FDG is a glucose analog that is taken up by glucose-using cells and phosphorylated by hexokinase (whose mitochondrial form is significantly elevated in rapidly growing malignant tumors).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Metabolic trapping of the radioactive glucose molecule allows the PET scan to be utilized.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The concentrations of imaged FDG tracer indicate tissue metabolic activity as it corresponds to the regional glucose uptake.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] FDG is used to explore the possibility of cancer spreading to other body sites (cancer metastasis).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] These FDG PET scans for detecting cancer metastasis are the most common in standard medical care (representing 90% of current scans).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The same tracer may also be used for the diagnosis of types of dementia.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Less often, other radioactive tracers, usually but not always labelled with fluorine-18 (18F), are used to image the tissue concentration of different kinds of molecules of interest inside the body.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Because the hydroxy group that is replaced by fluorine-18 to generate FDG is required for the next step in glucose metabolism in all cells, no further reactions occur in FDG.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Furthermore, most tissues (with the notable exception of liver and kidneys) cannot remove the phosphate added by hexokinase.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This means that FDG will remain trapped in any cell that takes it up until it decays, since phosphorylated sugars, due to their ionic charge, cannot exit from the cell.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This results in intense radiolabeling of tissues with high glucose uptake, such as the normal brain, liver, kidneys, and most cancers, which have a higher glucose uptake than most normal tissue due to the Warburg effect.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] As a result, FDG-PET can be used for diagnosis, staging, and monitoring treatment of cancers, particularly in Hodgkin lymphoma, non-Hodgkin lymphoma, and lung cancer.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] A few other isotopes and radiotracers are slowly being introduced into oncology for specific purposes.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] For example, 11C-labelled metomidate (11C-metomidate) has been used to detect tumors of adrenocortical origin.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Also, fluorodopa (FDOPA) PET/CT (also called F-18-DOPA PET/CT) has proven to be a more sensitive alternative to finding and also localizing pheochromocytoma than the iobenguane (MIBG) scan.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] For prostate cancer, there is growing interest in using a PET scan with radionuclides delivered via prostate-specific membrane antigen (PSMA) targeting ligand, a strategy which allows imaging the primary tumor and surrounding metastases in one scan.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The combination is referred to as a PSMA scan.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET imaging with oxygen-15 indirectly measures blood flow to the brain.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In this method, increased radioactivity signal indicates increased blood flow which is assumed to correlate with increased brain activity.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Because of its two-minute half-life, oxygen-15 must be piped directly from a medical cyclotron for such uses, which is difficult.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET imaging with FDG takes advantage of the fact that the brain is normally a rapid user of glucose.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Standard FDG PET of the brain measures regional glucose use and can be used in neuropathological diagnosis.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Brain pathologies such as Alzheimer's disease greatly decrease brain metabolism of both glucose and oxygen in tandem.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Therefore FDG PET of the brain may also be used to successfully differentiate Alzheimer's disease from other dementing processes, and also to make early diagnoses of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The advantage of FDG PET for these uses is its much wider availability.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In addition, some other fluorine-18 based radioactive tracers can be used to detect amyloid-beta plaques, a potential biomarker for Alzheimer's in the brain.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] These include florbetapir, flutemetamol, Pittsburgh compound B (PiB) and florbetaben.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET imaging with FDG can also be used for localization of "seizure focus".
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] A seizure focus will appear as hypometabolic during an interictal scan.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] These agents permit the visualization of neuroreceptor pools in the context of a plurality of neuropsychiatric and neurologic illnesses.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET may also be used for the diagnosis of hippocampal sclerosis, which causes epilepsy.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] FDG, and the less common tracers flumazenil and MPPF have been explored for this purpose.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] If the sclerosis is unilateral (right hippocampus or left hippocampus), FDG uptake can be compared with the healthy side.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Even if the diagnosis is difficult with MRI, it may be diagnosed with PET.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The development of a number of novel probes for non-invasive, *in-vivo* PET imaging of neuroaggregate in human brain has brought amyloid imaging close to clinical use.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The earliest amyloid imaging probes included [18F]FDDNP, developed at the University of California, Los Angeles, and Pittsburgh compound B (PiB), developed at the University of Pittsburgh.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] These probes permit the visualization of amyloid plaques in the brains of Alzheimer's patients and could assist clinicians in making a positive clinical diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease pre-mortem and aid in the development of novel anti-amyloid therapies.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] [11C]polymethylpentene (PMP) is a novel radiopharmaceutical used in PET imaging to determine the activity of the acetylcholinergic neurotransmitter system by acting as a substrate for acetylcholinesterase.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Post-mortem examination of Alzheimer's patients has shown decreased levels of acetylcholinesterase. [11C]PMP is used to map the acetylcholinesterase activity in the brain, which could allow for premortem diagnoses of Alzheimer's disease and assistance in monitoring treatments.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Avid Radiopharmaceuticals has developed and commercialized a compound called florbetapir that uses the longer-lasting radionuclide fluorine-18 to detect amyloid plaques using PET scans.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Recent advances in neuroimaging have focused on the development of tau-specific PET tracers such as [^18F] flortaucipir, [^18F]MK-6240, and [^18F]RO-948, which allow for in-vivo visualization of neurofibrillary tangles.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Tau imaging complements amyloid PET by providing a more direct measure of disease severity and progression in Alzheimer's disease and related tauopathies.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] These tracers have been increasingly used in longitudinal studies and clinical trials to monitor therapeutic response and to improve the accuracy of early differential diagnosis between Alzheimer's disease and other dementias.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Artificial intelligence-based image analysis methods are also being explored to automatically quantify tracer uptake and detect early disease patterns that may be missed by human observers.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Numerous compounds that bind selectively to neuroreceptors of interest in biological psychiatry have been radiolabeled with C-11 or F-18.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Radioligands that bind to dopamine receptors (D1, D2, reuptake transporter), serotonin receptors (5HT1A, 5HT2A, reuptake transporter), opioid receptors (mu and kappa), cholinergic receptors (nicotinic and muscarinic) and other sites have been used successfully in studies with human subjects.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Studies have been performed examining the state of these receptors in patients compared to healthy controls in schizophrenia, substance abuse, mood disorders and other psychiatric conditions.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET can also be used in image guided surgery for the treatment of intracranial tumors, arteriovenous malformations and other surgically treatable conditions.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Cardiac PET can be used to assess myocardial blood flow, and can also be used to diagnose heart conditions such as coronary artery disease, cardiac amyloidosis, and cardiac sarcoidosis.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] It has also been used to test the efficacy of novel anti-atherosclerosis therapies.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Commonly used radiotracers in cardiac PET are Rubidium-82, Nitrogen-13 ammonia and Oxygen-15 water.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Compared to cardiac SPECT, another commonly used nuclear medicine imaging modality in cardiology, PET offers superior image quality and improved diagnostic accuracy for coronary artery disease.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Despite the technical advantages of PET over SPECT, there is some debate over which modality is more cost effective: SPECT scanners are generally cheaper, and have a wider install base, though some studies have found that using PET results in less downstream healthcare utilisation.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Imaging infections with molecular imaging technologies can improve diagnosis and treatment follow-up.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Clinically, PET has been widely used to image bacterial infections using FDG to identify the infection-associated inflammatory response.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Three different PET contrast agents have been developed to image bacterial infections in vivo are [18F]maltose, [18F]maltohexaose, and [18F]2-fluorodeoxysorbitol (FDS).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] FDS has the added benefit of being able to target only Enterobacteriaceae.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In pre-clinical trials, a new drug can be radiolabeled and injected into animals.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Such scans are referred to as biodistribution studies.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The information regarding drug uptake, retention and elimination over time can be obtained quickly and cost-effectively compare to the older technique of killing and dissecting the animals.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Commonly, drug occupancy at a purported site of action can be inferred indirectly by competition studies between unlabeled drug and radiolabeled compounds to bind with specificity to the site.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] A single radioligand can be used this way to test many potential drug candidates for the same target.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] A related technique involves scanning with radioligands that compete with an endogenous (naturally occurring) substance at a given receptor to demonstrate that a drug causes the release of the natural substance.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] A miniature animal PET has been constructed that is small enough for a fully conscious rat to be scanned.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This RatCAP (rat conscious animal PET) allows animals to be scanned without the confounding effects of anesthesia.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET scanners designed specifically for imaging rodents, often referred to as microPET, as well as scanners for small primates, are marketed for academic and pharmaceutical research.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The scanners are based on microminiature scintillators and amplified avalanche photodiodes (APDs) through a system that uses single-chip silicon photomultipliers.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In 2018 the UC Davis School of Veterinary Medicine became the first veterinary center to employ a small clinical PET scanner as a scanner for clinical (rather than research) animal diagnosis.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Because of cost as well as the marginal utility of detecting cancer metastases in companion animals (the primary use of this modality), veterinary PET scanning is expected to be rarely available in the immediate future.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET imaging has been used for imaging muscles and bones.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] FDG is the most commonly used tracer for imaging muscles, and NaF-F18 is the most widely used tracer for imaging bones.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET is a feasible technique for studying skeletal muscles during exercise.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Also, PET can provide muscle activation data about deep-lying muscles (such as the vastus intermedialis and the gluteus minimus) compared to techniques like electromyography, which can be used only on superficial muscles directly under the skin.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] However, a disadvantage is that PET provides no timing information about muscle activation because it has to be measured after the exercise is completed.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This is due to the time it takes for FDG to accumulate in the activated muscles.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Together with [18F]sodium floride, PET for bone imaging has been in use for 60 years for measuring regional bone metabolism and blood flow using static and dynamic scans.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Researchers have recently started using [18F]sodium fluoride to study bone metastasis as well.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET scanning is non-invasive, but it does involve exposure to ionizing radiation.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] For a typical dose (245 MBq) of FDG, one of the most common radiotracers used for PET neuroimaging and cancer patient management, the effective radiation dose is 4.7 mSv.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] For combined PET–CT scanning, the radiation exposure contributed by the CT scan may be substantial - ranging from around 3–26 mSv (for a 70 kg person, and depending on the coverage and intended use of the scan).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The amount of radiation in a typical FDG PET-CT scan is similar to the effective dose of spending one year in the American city of Denver, Colorado (12.4 mSv/year).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] For comparison, radiation dosage for other medical procedures range from 0.02 mSv for a chest X-ray and 6.5–8 mSv for a CT scan of the chest.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Average civil aircrews are exposed to 3 mSv/year, and the IAEA recommend that whole body effective dose for nuclear energy workers is 20 mSv/year (when averaged over 5 years) and does not exceed 50 mSv in a given year.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The radioactive substance used clinical practices in PET scanning is a simple sugar called fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Radionuclides are incorporated either into compounds normally used by the body such as glucose (or glucose analogues), water, or ammonia, or into molecules that bind to receptors or other sites of drug action.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Such labelled compounds are known as radiotracers.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET technology can be used to trace the biologic pathway of any compound in living humans (and many other species as well), provided it can be radiolabeled with a PET isotope.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Radiotracers for new target molecules and processes are continuing to be synthesized.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] As of this writing there are already dozens in clinical use and hundreds applied in research.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In 2020 by far the most commonly used radiotracer in clinical PET scanning is the carbohydrate derivative FDG.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This radiotracer is used in essentially all scans for oncology and most scans in neurology, thus makes up the large majority of radiotracer (>95%) used in PET and PET–CT scanning.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Due to the short half-lives of most positron-emitting radioisotopes, the radiotracers have traditionally been produced using a cyclotron in close proximity to the PET imaging facility.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The half-life of fluorine-18 is long enough that radiotracers labeled with fluorine-18 can be manufactured commercially at offsite locations and shipped to imaging centers.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Recently rubidium-82 generators have become commercially available.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] These contain strontium-82, which decays by electron capture to produce positron-emitting rubidium-82.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The use of positron-emitting isotopes of metals in PET scans has been reviewed, including elements not listed above, such as lanthanides.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The isotope 89Zr has been applied to the tracking and quantification of molecular antibodies with PET cameras (a method called "immuno-PET").
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The biological half-life of antibodies is typically on the order of days, see daclizumab and erenumab by way of example.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] To visualize and quantify the distribution of such antibodies in the body, the PET isotope 89Zr is well suited because its physical half-life matches the typical biological half-life of antibodies, see table above.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] To conduct the scan, a short-lived radioactive tracer isotope is injected into the living subject (usually into blood circulation).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Each tracer atom has been chemically incorporated into a biologically active molecule.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] There is a waiting period while the active molecule becomes concentrated in tissues of interest.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Then the subject is placed in the imaging scanner.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The molecule most commonly used for this purpose is FDG, a sugar, for which the waiting period is typically an hour.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] During the scan, a record of tissue concentration is made as the tracer decays.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] As the radioisotope undergoes positron emission decay (also known as positive beta decay), it emits a positron, an antiparticle of the electron with opposite charge.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The emitted positron travels in tissue for a short distance (typically less than 1 mm, but dependent on the isotope), during which time it loses kinetic energy, until it decelerates to a point where it can interact with an electron.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The encounter annihilates both electron and positron, producing a pair of annihilation (gamma) photons moving in approximately opposite directions.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] These are detected when they reach a scintillator in the scanning device, creating a burst of light which is detected by photomultiplier tubes or silicon avalanche photodiodes (Si APD).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The technique depends on simultaneous or coincident detection of the pair of photons moving in approximately opposite directions (they would be exactly opposite in their center of mass frame, but the scanner has no way to know this, and so has a built-in slight direction-error tolerance).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Photons that do not arrive in temporal "pairs" (i.e. within a timing-window of a few nanoseconds) are ignored.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The most significant fraction of electron–positron annihilations results in two 511 keV gamma photons being emitted at almost exactly 180 degrees to each other.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Hence, it is possible to localize their source along a straight line of coincidence (also called the **line of response**, or **LOR**).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In practice, the LOR has a non-zero width as the emitted photons are not exactly 180 degrees apart.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] If the resolving time of the detectors is less than 500 picoseconds rather than about 10 nanoseconds, it is possible to localize the event to a segment of a chord, whose length is determined by the detector timing resolution.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] As the timing resolution improves, the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of the image will improve, requiring fewer events to achieve the same image quality.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This technology is not yet common, but it is available on some new systems.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The raw data collected by a PET scanner are a list of 'coincidence events' representing near-simultaneous detection (typically, within a window of 6 to 12 nanoseconds of each other) of annihilation photons by a pair of detectors.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Each coincidence event represents a line in space connecting the two detectors along which the positron emission occurred (i.e., the line of response (LOR)).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Analytical techniques, much like the reconstruction of computed tomography (CT) and single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT) data, are commonly used, although the data set collected in PET is much poorer than CT, so reconstruction techniques are more difficult.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Coincidence events can be grouped into projection images, called sinograms.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The sinograms are sorted by the angle of each view and tilt (for 3D images).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The sinogram images are analogous to the projections captured by CT scanners, and can be reconstructed in a similar way.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The statistics of data thereby obtained are much worse than those obtained through transmission tomography.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] A normal PET data set has millions of counts for the whole acquisition, while the CT can reach a few billion counts.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This contributes to PET images appearing "noisier" than CT.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Filtered back projection (FBP) has been frequently used to reconstruct images from the projections.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This algorithm has the advantage of being simple while having a low requirement for computing resources.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Disadvantages are that shot noise in the raw data is prominent in the reconstructed images, and areas of high tracer uptake tend to form streaks across the image.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Also, FBP treats the data deterministically – it does not account for the inherent randomness associated with PET data, thus requiring all the pre-reconstruction corrections described above.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Good's roughness method may yield superior performance to expectation-maximization-based methods which involve a Poisson likelihood function but do not involve such a prior.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] One option for estimating attenuation coefficients is via a transmission scan, using a 68Ge rod source that is rotated around the patient Transmission scans directly measure attenuation values at 511 keV.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] With PET-CT scanners the 511 keV photon attenuation coefficients can be estimated using the Hounsfield units from the CT scan.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Attenuation correction in PET-MRI scanners is more challenging, as the MRI images do not directly contain information on about the tissue attenuation coefficients, and the scanner bores are too narrow for a transmission scan.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Several methods have been proposed for PET-MRI attenuation coefficient, including machine learning, algorithms to directly estimate attenuation coefficients from the MRI or emission data, and atlas-based approaches (where the MRI scan is co-registered with a database of CT images).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] While attenuation-corrected images are generally more faithful representations, the correction process is itself susceptible to significant artifacts.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] As a result, both corrected and uncorrected images are often reconstructed and read together.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Allow coincidences to be detected between rings as well as within rings, then reconstruct the entire volume together (3D).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] 3D techniques have better sensitivity (because more coincidences are detected and used) hence less noise, but are more sensitive to the effects of scatter and random coincidences, as well as requiring greater computer resources.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The advent of sub-nanosecond timing resolution detectors affords better random coincidence rejection, thus favoring 3D image reconstruction.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PET scans are increasingly read alongside CT or MRI scans, with the combination (co-registration) giving both anatomic and metabolic information (i.e., what the structure is, and what it is doing biochemically).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Because PET imaging is most useful in combination with anatomical imaging, such as CT, modern PET scanners are now available with integrated high-end multi-detector-row CT scanners (PET–CT).
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This is very useful in showing detailed views of moving organs or structures with higher anatomical variation, which is more common outside the brain.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] At the Jülich Institute of Neurosciences and Biophysics, the world's largest PET–MRI device began operation in April 2009.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] A 9.4-tesla magnetic resonance tomograph (MRT) combined with a PET.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Presently, only the head and brain can be imaged at these high magnetic field strengths.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] For brain imaging, registration of CT, MRI and PET scans may be accomplished without the need for an integrated PET–CT or PET–MRI scanner by using a device known as the N-localizer.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The minimization of radiation dose to the subject is an attractive feature of the use of short-lived radionuclides.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Besides its established role as a diagnostic technique, PET has an expanding role as a method to assess the response to therapy, in particular, cancer therapy, where the risk to the patient from lack of knowledge about disease progress is much greater than the risk from the test radiation.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Since the tracers are radioactive they are generally not used with those who are pregnant.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Limitations to the widespread use of PET arise from the high costs of cyclotrons needed to produce the short-lived radionuclides for PET scanning and the need for specially adapted on-site chemical synthesis apparatus to produce the radiopharmaceuticals after radioisotope preparation.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Organic radiotracer molecules that will contain a positron-emitting radioisotope cannot be synthesized first and then the radioisotope prepared within them, because bombardment with a cyclotron to prepare the radioisotope destroys any organic carrier for it.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Instead, the isotope must be prepared first, then the chemistry to prepare any organic radiotracer (such as FDG) accomplished very quickly, in the short time before the isotope decays.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Few hospitals and universities are capable of maintaining such systems, and most clinical PET is supported by third-party suppliers of radiotracers that can supply many sites simultaneously.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In recent years a few on-site cyclotrons with integrated shielding and "hot labs" (automated chemistry labs that are able to work with radioisotopes) have begun to accompany PET units to remote hospitals.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The presence of the small on-site cyclotron promises to expand in the future as the cyclotrons shrink in response to the high cost of isotope transportation to remote PET machines.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In recent years the shortage of PET scans has been alleviated in the US, as rollout of radiopharmacies to supply radioisotopes has grown 30 percent per year.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Because the half-life of fluorine-18 is about two hours, the prepared dose of a radiopharmaceutical bearing this radionuclide will undergo multiple half-lives of decay during the working day.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] This necessitates frequent recalibration of the remaining dose (determination of activity per unit volume) and careful planning with respect to patient scheduling.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The concept of emission and transmission tomography was introduced by David E.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Kuhl, Luke Chapman and Roy Edwards in the late 1950s.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Their work would lead to the design and construction of several tomographic instruments at Washington University School of Medicine and later at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In the 1960s and 70s tomographic imaging instruments and techniques were further developed by Michel Ter-Pogossian, Michael E.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Hoffman and others at Washington University School of Medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Work by Gordon Brownell, Charles Burnham and their associates at the Massachusetts General Hospital beginning in the 1950s contributed significantly to the development of PET technology and included the first demonstration of annihilation radiation for medical imaging.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Their innovations, including the use of light pipes and volumetric analysis, have been important in the deployment of PET imaging.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In 1961, James Robertson and his associates at Brookhaven National Laboratory built the first single-plane PET scan, nicknamed the "head-shrinker".
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] One of the factors most responsible for the acceptance of positron imaging was the development of radiopharmaceuticals.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The compound was first administered to two normal human volunteers by Abass Alavi in August 1976 at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Brain images obtained with an ordinary (non-PET) nuclear scanner demonstrated the concentration of FDG in that organ.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Later, the substance was used in dedicated positron tomographic scanners, to yield the modern procedure.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The logical extension of positron instrumentation was a design using two two-dimensional arrays.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] PC-I was the first instrument using this concept and was designed in 1968, completed in 1969 and reported in 1972.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The first applications of PC-I in tomographic mode as distinguished from the computed tomographic mode were reported in 1970.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] It soon became clear to many of those involved in PET development that a circular or cylindrical array of detectors was the logical next step in PET instrumentation.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] Although many investigators took this approach, James Robertson and Zang-Hee Cho were the first to propose a ring system that has become the prototype of the current shape of PET.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The first multislice cylindrical array PET scanner was completed in 1974 at the Mallinckrodt Institute of Radiology by the group led by Ter-Pogossian.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The PET–CT scanner, attributed to David Townsend and Ronald Nutt, was named by *Time* as the medical invention of the year in 2000.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In Canada, PET scan funding varies by province.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In Ontario, as of October 2025, there is no charge to the patient for any PET scans funded as part of the PET Scans Ontario Program.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The program funds routine PET services for indications where sufficient evidence exists that the scan benefits the patient and offers advantages over other imaging tests.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In the United States, PET scan costs vary significantly by location, facility type, and insurance status.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] According to Medicare's 2026 payment data, a whole-body PET scan has a national average total cost of $872, with the patient paying approximately $174 after Medicare coverage.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In the United Kingdom, the National Health Service provides PET-CT scans free at point of use for eligible patients.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] In Australia, Medicare subsidies are available for eligible PET services.
[src:pet-imaging/positron-emission-tomography] The overall performance of PET systems can be evaluated by quality control tools such as the Jaszczak phantom.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The **positron** or **antielectron** is the particle with an electric charge of +1*e*, a spin of 1/2 *ħ* (the same as the electron), and the same mass as an electron.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] It is the antiparticle (antimatter counterpart) of the electron.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] When a positron collides with an electron, annihilation occurs.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] If this collision occurs at low energies, it results in the production of two or more photons.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Positrons can be created by positron emission radioactive decay (through weak interactions), or by pair production from a sufficiently energetic photon which is interacting with an atom in a material.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] In 1928, Paul Dirac published a paper proposing that electrons can have both a positive and negative charge.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] This paper introduced the Dirac equation, a unification of quantum mechanics, special relativity, and the then-new concept of electron spin to explain the Zeeman effect.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The paper did not explicitly predict a new particle but did allow for electrons having either positive or negative energy as solutions.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Hermann Weyl then published a paper discussing the mathematical implications of the negative energy solution.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The positive-energy solution explained experimental results, but Dirac was puzzled by the equally valid negative-energy solution that the mathematical model allowed.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Quantum mechanics did not allow the negative energy solution to simply be ignored, as classical mechanics often did in such equations; the dual solution implied the possibility of an electron spontaneously jumping between positive and negative energy states.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] However, no such transition had yet been observed experimentally.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Dirac wrote a follow-up paper in December 1929 that attempted to explain the unavoidable negative-energy solution for the relativistic electron.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The paper also explored the possibility of the proton being an island in this sea, and that it might actually be a negative-energy electron.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Dirac acknowledged that the proton having a much greater mass than the electron was a problem, but expressed "hope" that a future theory would resolve the issue.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Robert Oppenheimer argued strongly against the proton being the negative-energy electron solution to Dirac's equation.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] He asserted that if it were, the hydrogen atom would rapidly self-destruct.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Weyl in 1931 showed that the negative-energy electron must have the same mass as that of the positive-energy electron.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Ernst Stueckelberg, and later Richard Feynman, proposed an interpretation of the positron as an electron moving backward in time, reinterpreting the negative-energy solutions of the Dirac equation.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Electrons moving backward in time would have a positive electric charge.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] John Archibald Wheeler invoked this concept to explain the identical properties shared by all electrons, suggesting that "they are all the same electron" with a complex, self-intersecting worldline.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Beginning in 1923, while using a Wilson cloud chamber to study the Compton effect, Dmitri Skobeltsyn observed tracks that acted like electrons but curved in the opposite direction in an applied magnetic field.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Skobeltsyn presented photographs with this phenomenon in a conference in the University of Cambridge, on 23–27 July 1928.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Similar photographic evidence had been seen by Irene and Frederic Joliot-Curie and others but no one at the time had an explanation for these anomalous tracks.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Skobeltsyn paved the way for the eventual discovery of the positron by two important contributions: adding a magnetic field to his cloud chamber (in 1925), and by discovering charged particle cosmic rays, for which he is credited in Carl David Anderson's Nobel lecture.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Likewise, in 1929 Chung-Yao Chao, a Chinese graduate student at Caltech, noticed some anomalous results that indicated particles behaving like electrons, but with a positive charge, though the results were inconclusive and the phenomenon was not pursued.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Fifty years later, Anderson acknowledged that his discovery was inspired by the work of his Caltech classmate Chung-Yao Chao.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Anderson used the same radioactive source but adopted a magnet cloud chamber which allowed him to see the anti-electron tracks.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Anderson discovered the positron on 2 August 1932, for which he won the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1936.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Anderson did not coin the term *positron*, but allowed it at the suggestion of the *Physical Review* journal editor to whom he submitted his discovery paper in late 1932.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The positron was the first evidence of antimatter and was discovered when Anderson allowed cosmic rays to pass through a cloud chamber and a lead plate.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] A magnet surrounded this apparatus, causing particles to bend in different directions based on their electric charge.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The ion trail left by each positron appeared on the photographic plate with a curvature matching the mass-to-charge ratio of an electron, but in a direction that showed its charge was positive.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Anderson wrote in retrospect that the positron could have been discovered earlier based on Chung-Yao Chao's work, if only it had been followed up on.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Frédéric and Irène Joliot-Curie in Paris had evidence of positrons in old photographs when Anderson's results came out, but they had dismissed them as protons.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The positron had also been contemporaneously discovered by Patrick Blackett and Giuseppe Occhialini at the Cavendish Laboratory in 1932.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Blackett and Occhialini had delayed publication to obtain more solid evidence, so Anderson was able to publish the discovery first.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Positrons are produced, together with neutrinos naturally in β+ decays of naturally occurring radioactive isotopes (for example, potassium-40) and in interactions of gamma quanta (emitted by radioactive nuclei) with matter.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Antineutrinos are another kind of antiparticle produced by natural radioactivity (β− decay).
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Many different kinds of antiparticles are also produced by (and contained in) cosmic rays.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] In research published in 2011 by the American Astronomical Society, positrons were discovered originating above thunderstorm clouds; positrons are produced in gamma-ray flashes created by electrons accelerated by strong electric fields in the clouds.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Antiprotons have also been found to exist in the Van Allen Belts around the Earth by the PAMELA module.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Antiparticles, of which the most common are antineutrinos and positrons due to their low mass, are also produced in any environment with a sufficiently high temperature (mean particle energy greater than the pair production threshold).
[src:pet-imaging/positron] During the period of baryogenesis, when the universe was extremely hot and dense, matter and antimatter were continually produced and annihilated.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The presence of remaining matter, and absence of detectable remaining antimatter, also called baryon asymmetry, is attributed to CP-violation: a violation of the CP-symmetry relating matter to antimatter.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The exact mechanism of this violation during baryogenesis remains a mystery.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Positron production from radioactive β+ decay can be considered both artificial and natural production, as the generation of the radioisotope can be natural or artificial.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Perhaps the best known naturally occurring radioisotope which produces positrons is potassium-40, a long-lived isotope of potassium which occurs as a primordial isotope of potassium.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Even though it is a small percentage of potassium (0.0117%), it is the single most abundant radioisotope in the human body.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] In a human body of 70 kg (150 lb) mass, about 4,400 nuclei of 40K decay per second.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The activity of natural potassium is 31 Bq/g.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] About 0.001% of these 40K decays produce about 4,000 natural positrons per day in the human body.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] These positrons soon find an electron, undergo annihilation, and produce pairs of 511 keV photons, in a process similar (but much lower intensity) to that which happens during a PET scan nuclear medicine procedure.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Recent observations indicate black holes and neutron stars produce vast amounts of positron–electron plasma in astrophysical jets.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Large clouds of positron–electron plasma have also been associated with neutron stars.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Satellite experiments have found evidence of positrons (as well as a few antiprotons) in primary cosmic rays, amounting to less than 1% of the particles in primary cosmic rays.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] However, the fraction of positrons in cosmic rays has been measured more recently with improved accuracy, especially at much higher energy levels, and the fraction of positrons has been seen to be greater in these higher energy cosmic rays.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] These do not appear to be the products of large amounts of antimatter from the Big Bang, or indeed complex antimatter in the universe (evidence for which is lacking, see below).
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Rather, the antimatter in cosmic rays appear to consist of only these two elementary particles.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Recent theories suggest the source of such positrons may come from annihilation of dark matter particles, acceleration of positrons to high energies in astrophysical objects, and production of high energy positrons in the interactions of cosmic ray nuclei with interstellar gas.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Preliminary results from the presently operating Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer (*AMS-02*) on board the International Space Station show that positrons in the cosmic rays arrive with no directionality, and with energies that range from 0.5 GeV to 500 GeV.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Positron fraction peaks at a maximum of about 16% of total electron+positron events, around an energy of 275 ± 32 GeV.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] At higher energies, up to 500 GeV, the ratio of positrons to electrons begins to fall again.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The absolute flux of positrons also begins to fall before 500 GeV, but peaks at energies far higher than electron energies, which peak about 10 GeV.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] These results on interpretation have been suggested to be due to positron production in annihilation events of massive dark matter particles.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Positrons, like anti-protons, do not appear to originate from any hypothetical "antimatter" regions of the universe.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] On the contrary, there is no evidence of complex antimatter atomic nuclei, such as antihelium nuclei (i.e., anti-alpha particles), in cosmic rays.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] A prototype of the *AMS-02* designated *AMS-01*, was flown into space aboard the Space Shuttle *Discovery* on STS-91 in June 1998.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] By not detecting any antihelium at all, the *AMS-01* established an upper limit of 1.1×10−6 for the antihelium to helium flux ratio.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Physicists at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in California have used a short, ultra-intense laser to irradiate a millimeter-thick gold target and produce more than 100 billion positrons.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Presently significant lab production of 5 MeV positron–electron beams allows investigation of multiple characteristics such as how different elements react to 5 MeV positron interactions or impacts, how energy is transferred to particles, and the shock effect of gamma-ray bursts.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Future experiments offer the possibility to study physics relevant to extreme astrophysical environments where copious electron-positron pairs are generated, such as gamma-ray bursts, fast radio bursts and blazar jets.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Certain kinds of particle accelerator experiments involve colliding positrons and electrons at relativistic speeds.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The high impact energy and the mutual annihilation of these matter/antimatter opposites create a fountain of diverse subatomic particles.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Physicists study the results of these collisions to test theoretical predictions and to search for new kinds of particles.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] The ALPHA experiment combines positrons with antiprotons to study properties of antihydrogen.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] Gamma rays, emitted indirectly by a positron-emitting radionuclide (tracer), are detected in positron emission tomography (PET) scanners used in hospitals.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] PET scanners create detailed three-dimensional images of metabolic activity within the human body.
[src:pet-imaging/positron] An experimental tool called positron annihilation spectroscopy (PAS) is used in materials research to detect variations in density, defects, displacements, or even voids, within a solid material.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] A **radioactive tracer**, **radiotracer**, or **radioactive label** is a synthetic derivative of a natural compound in which one or more atoms have been replaced by a radionuclide (a radioactive atom).
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] By virtue of its radioactive decay, it can be used to explore the mechanism of chemical reactions by tracing the path that the radioisotope follows from reactants to products.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] **Radiolabeling** or **radiotracing** is thus the radioactive form of isotopic labeling.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In biological contexts, experiments that use radioisotope tracers are sometimes called **radioisotope feeding** experiments.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Radioisotopes of hydrogen, carbon, phosphorus, sulfur, and iodine have been used extensively to trace the path of biochemical reactions.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] A radioactive tracer can also be used to track the distribution of a substance within a natural system such as a cell or tissue, or as a flow tracer to track fluid flow.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Radioactive tracers are also used to determine the location of fractures created by hydraulic fracturing in natural gas production.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Radioactive tracers form the basis of a variety of imaging systems, such as, PET scans, SPECT scans and technetium scans.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Radiocarbon dating uses the naturally occurring carbon-14 isotope as an isotopic label.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In radiopharmaceutical sciences some misuse of established scientific terms exist.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Therefore an international "Working Group on Nomenclature in Radiopharmaceutical Chemistry and Related Areas" was formed in 2015 by the Society of Radiopharmaceutical Sciences (SRS).
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Their goal was to clarify terminology and to establish a standardized nomenclature through global consensus, ensuring consistency and accuracy within the discipline.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Isotopes of a chemical element differ only in the mass number.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] For example, the isotopes of hydrogen can be written as 1H, 2H and 3H, with the mass number superscripted to the left.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] When the atomic nucleus of an isotope is unstable, compounds containing this isotope are radioactive.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Tritium is an example of a radioactive isotope.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The principle behind the use of radioactive tracers is that an atom in a chemical compound is replaced by another atom, of the same chemical element.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The substituting atom, however, is a radioactive isotope.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] This process is often called radioactive labeling.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The power of the technique is due to the fact that radioactive decay is much more energetic than chemical reactions.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Therefore, the radioactive isotope can be present in low concentration and its presence detected by sensitive radiation detectors such as Geiger counters and scintillation counters.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] George de Hevesy won the 1943 Nobel Prize for Chemistry "for his work on the use of isotopes as tracers in the study of chemical processes".
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] A radioactive compound is introduced into a living organism and the radio-isotope provides a means to construct an image showing the way in which that compound and its reaction products are distributed around the organism.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The commonly used radioisotopes have short half lives and so do not occur in nature in large amounts.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] One of the most important processes is absorption of a neutron by an atomic nucleus, in which the mass number of the element concerned increases by 1 for each neutron absorbed.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In this case the atomic mass increases, but the element is unchanged.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In other cases the product nucleus is unstable and decays, typically emitting protons, electrons (beta particle) or alpha particles.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] When a nucleus loses a proton the atomic number decreases by 1.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Neutron irradiation is performed in a nuclear reactor.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The other main method used to synthesize radioisotopes is proton bombardment.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The proton are accelerated to high energy either in a cyclotron or a linear accelerator.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Tritium has a half-life 4500±8 days (approximately 12.32 years) and it decays by beta decay.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The electrons produced have an average energy of 5.7 keV.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Because the emitted electrons have relatively low energy, the detection efficiency by scintillation counting is rather low.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] However, hydrogen atoms are present in all organic compounds, so tritium is frequently used as a tracer in biochemical studies.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 11C decays by positron emission with a half-life of ca.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 11C is one of the isotopes often used in positron emission tomography.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 14C decays by beta decay, with a half-life of 5730 years.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is continuously produced in the upper atmosphere of the earth, so it occurs at a trace level in the environment.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] However, it is not practical to use naturally occurring 14C for tracer studies.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Instead it is made by neutron irradiation of the isotope 13C which occurs naturally in carbon at about the 1.1% level.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 14C has been used extensively to trace the progress of organic molecules through metabolic pathways.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 13N decays by positron emission with a half-life of 9.97 min.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 13N is used in positron emission tomography (PET scan).
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 15O decays by positron emission with a half-life of 122 seconds.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is used in positron emission tomography.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 18F decays predominantly by β emission, with a half-life of 109.8 min.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is made by proton bombardment of 18O in a cyclotron or linear particle accelerator.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is an important isotope in the radiopharmaceutical industry.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] For example, it is used to make labeled fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) or D-3-[18F]fluoroalanine for application in PET scans.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It decays by beta decay with a half-life of 14.29 days.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is commonly used to study protein phosphorylation by kinases in biochemistry.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 33P is made in relatively low yield by neutron bombardment of 31P.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is also a beta-emitter, with a half-life of 25.4 days.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Though more expensive than 32P, the emitted electrons are less energetic, permitting better resolution in, for example, DNA sequencing.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Both isotopes are useful for labeling nucleotides and other species that contain a phosphate group.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It decays by beta-decay with a half-life of 87.51 days.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is used to label the sulfur-containing amino-acids methionine and cysteine.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] When a sulfur atom replaces an oxygen atom in a phosphate group on a nucleotide a thiophosphate is produced, so 35S can also be used to trace a phosphate group.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 99mTc is a very versatile radioisotope, and is the most commonly used radioisotope tracer in medicine.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is easy to produce in a technetium-99m generator, by decay of 99Mo.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The molybdenum isotope has a half-life of approximately 66 hours (2.75 days), so the generator has a useful life of about two weeks.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Most commercial 99mTc generators use column chromatography, in which 99Mo in the form of molybdate, MoO42− is adsorbed onto acid alumina (Al2O3).
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] When the 99Mo decays it forms pertechnetate TcO4−, which because of its single charge is less tightly bound to the alumina.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Pulling normal saline solution through the column of immobilized 99Mo elutes the soluble 99mTc, resulting in a saline solution containing the 99mTc as the dissolved sodium salt of the pertechnetate.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The pertechnetate is treated with a reducing agent such as Sn2+ and a ligand.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Different ligands form coordination complexes which give the technetium enhanced affinity for particular sites in the human body.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 99mTc decays by gamma emission, with a half-life: 6.01 hours.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The short half-life ensures that the body-concentration of the radioisotope falls effectively to zero in a few days.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 123I is produced by proton irradiation of 124Xe.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The caesium isotope produced is unstable and decays to 123I.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The isotope is usually supplied as the iodide and hypoiodate in dilute sodium hydroxide solution, at high isotopic purity.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 123I has also been produced at Oak Ridge National Laboratories by proton bombardment of 123Te.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 123I decays by electron capture with a half-life of 13.22 hours.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The emitted 159 keV gamma ray is used in single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT).
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 125I is frequently used in radioimmunoassays because of its relatively long half-life (59 days) and ability to be detected with high sensitivity by gamma counters.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 129I is present in the environment as a result of the testing of nuclear weapons in the atmosphere.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It was also produced in the Chernobyl and Fukushima disasters.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 129I decays with a half-life of 15.7 million years, with low-energy beta and gamma emissions.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] It is not used as a tracer, though its presence in living organisms, including human beings, can be characterized by measurement of the gamma rays.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Many other isotopes have been used in specialized radiopharmacological studies.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The most widely used is 67Ga for gallium scans.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] 67Ga is used because, like 99mTc, it is a gamma-ray emitter and various ligands can be attached to the Ga3+ ion, forming a coordination complex which may have selective affinity for particular sites in the human body.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] An extensive list of radioactive tracers used in hydraulic fracturing can be found below.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In metabolism research, tritium and 14C-labeled glucose are commonly used in glucose clamps to measure rates of glucose uptake, fatty acid synthesis, and other metabolic processes.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] While radioactive tracers are sometimes still used in human studies, stable isotope tracers such as 13C are more commonly used in current human clamp studies.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Radioactive tracers are also used to study lipoprotein metabolism in humans and experimental animals.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In medicine, tracers are applied in a number of tests, such as 99mTc in autoradiography and nuclear medicine, including single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), positron emission tomography (PET) and scintigraphy.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] The urea breath test for helicobacter pylori commonly used a dose of 14C labeled urea to detect h. pylori infection.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] If the labeled urea was metabolized by h. pylori in the stomach, the patient's breath would contain labeled carbon dioxide.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In recent years, the use of substances enriched in the non-radioactive isotope 13C has become the preferred method, avoiding patient exposure to radioactivity.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In hydraulic fracturing, radioactive tracer isotopes are injected with hydraulic fracturing fluid to determine the injection profile and location of created fractures.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] Tracers with different half-lives are used for each stage of hydraulic fracturing.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] In the United States amounts per injection of radionuclide are listed in the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) guidelines.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] According to the NRC, some of the most commonly used tracers include antimony-124, bromine-82, iodine-125, iodine-131, iridium-192, and scandium-46.
[src:pet-imaging/radioactive-tracer] A 2003 publication by the International Atomic Energy Agency confirms the frequent use of most of the tracers above, and says that manganese-56, sodium-24, technetium-99m, silver-110m, argon-41, and xenon-133 are also used extensively because they are easily identified and measured.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] A **scintillator** (/ˈsɪntɪleɪtər/ *SIN-til-ay-ter*) is a material that exhibits scintillation (also termed *radioluminescence*), a kind of luminescence, when excited by ionizing radiation.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Luminescent materials, when struck by an incoming particle, absorb its energy and scintillate (i.e. re-emit the absorbed energy in the form of light).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Sometimes, the excited state is metastable, so the relaxation back down from the excited state to lower states is delayed (necessitating anywhere from a few nanoseconds to hours depending on the material).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The process then corresponds to one of two phenomena: delayed fluorescence or phosphorescence.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The correspondence depends on the type of transition and hence the wavelength of the emitted optical photon.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] A scintillation detector or scintillation counter is obtained when a scintillator is coupled to an electronic light sensor such as a photomultiplier tube (PMT), photodiode, or silicon photomultiplier (SiPM).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] PMTs absorb the light emitted by the scintillator and re-emit it in the form of electrons via the photoelectric effect.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The subsequent multiplication of those electrons (sometimes called photo-electrons) results in an electrical pulse which can then be analyzed and yield meaningful information about the particle that originally struck the scintillator.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Vacuum photodiodes are similar but do not amplify the signal while silicon photodiodes, on the other hand, detect incoming photons by the excitation of charge carriers directly in the silicon.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Silicon photomultipliers consist of an array of photodiodes which are reverse-biased with sufficient voltage to operate in avalanche mode, enabling each pixel of the array to be sensitive to single photons.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The first device which used a scintillator was built in 1903, by Sir William Crookes and used a ZnS screen.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The scintillations produced by the screen were visible if viewed by a microscope in a darkened room; the device was known as a spinthariscope.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The technique led to a number of important discoveries but was obviously tedious.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Scintillators gained additional attention in 1944, when Curran and Baker replaced the naked eye measurement with the newly developed PMT.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This was the birth of the modern scintillation detector.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Scintillators are used by the American government as Homeland Security radiation detectors.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Scintillators can also be used in particle detectors, new energy resource exploration, X-ray security, nuclear cameras, computed tomography and gas exploration.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Other applications of scintillators include CT scanners and gamma cameras in medical diagnostics, and screens in older style CRT computer monitors and television sets.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Scintillators have also been proposed as part of theoretical models for the harnessing of gamma-ray energy through the photovoltaic effect, for example in a nuclear battery.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The use of a scintillator in conjunction with a photomultiplier tube finds wide use in hand-held survey meters used for detecting and measuring radioactive contamination and monitoring nuclear material.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Scintillators generate light in fluorescent tubes, to convert the ultra-violet of the discharge into visible light.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Scintillation detectors are also used in the petroleum industry as detectors for Gamma Ray logs.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] There are many desired properties of scintillators, such as high density, fast operation speed, low cost, radiation hardness, production capability, and durability of operational parameters.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] High density reduces the material size of showers for high-energy γ-quanta and electrons.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The range of Compton scattered photons for lower energy γ-rays is also decreased via high density materials.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This results in high segmentation of the detector and leads to better spatial resolution.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Usually high density materials have heavy ions in the lattice (e.g., lead, cadmium), significantly increasing the contribution of photoelectric effect (~Z4).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The increased photo-fraction is important for some applications such as positron emission tomography.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] High stopping power for electromagnetic component of the ionizing radiation needs greater photo-fraction; this allows for a compact detector.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] High operating speed is needed for good resolution of spectra.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Precision of time measurement with a scintillation detector is proportional to √τsc.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Short decay times are important for the measurement of time intervals and for the operation in fast coincidence circuits.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] High density and fast response time can allow detection of rare events in particle physics.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Particle energy deposited in the material of a scintillator is proportional to the scintillator's response.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Charged particles, γ-quanta and ions have different slopes when their response is measured.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Thus, scintillators could be used to identify various types of γ-quanta and particles in fluxes of mixed radiation.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Another consideration of scintillators is the cost of producing them.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Most crystal scintillators require high-purity chemicals and sometimes rare-earth metals that are fairly expensive.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Not only are the materials an expenditure, but many crystals require expensive furnaces and almost six months of growth and analyzing time.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Currently, other scintillators are being researched for reduced production cost.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Ruggedness and good behavior under high temperature may be desirable where resistance to vibration and high temperature is necessary (e.g., oil exploration).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The practical choice of a scintillator material is usually a compromise among those properties to best fit a given application.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The light output is a strong function of the type of incident particle or photon and of its energy, which therefore strongly influences the type of scintillation material to be used for a particular application.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The presence of quenching effects results in reduced light output (i.e., reduced scintillation efficiency).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Quenching refers to all radiationless de‑excitation processes in which the excitation is degraded mainly to heat.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The light output is often quantified as a number of scintillation photons produced per keV of deposited energy.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Typical numbers are (when the incident particle is an electron): ≈40 photons/keV for NaI(Tl), ~10 photons/keV for plastic scintillators, and ~8 photons/keV for bismuth germanate (BGO).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Scintillation detectors are generally assumed to be linear.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This assumption is based on two requirements: (1) that the light output of the scintillator is proportional to the energy of the incident radiation; (2) that the electrical pulse produced by the photomultiplier tube is proportional to the emitted scintillation light.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The linearity assumption is usually a good rough approximation, although deviations can occur (especially pronounced for particles heavier than the proton at low energies).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Resistance and good behavior under high-temperature, high-vibration environments is especially important for applications such as oil exploration (wireline logging, measurement while drilling).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] For most scintillators, light output and scintillation decay time depends on the temperature.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This dependence can largely be ignored for room-temperature applications since it is usually weak.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The dependence on the temperature is also weaker for organic scintillators than it is for inorganic crystals, such as NaI-Tl or BGO.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Strong dependence of decay time on the temperature in BGO scintillator is used for remote monitoring of temperature in vacuum environment.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The coupled PMTs also exhibit temperature sensitivity, and can be damaged if submitted to mechanical shock.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Hence, high temperature rugged PMTs should be used for high-temperature, high-vibration applications.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The time evolution of the number of emitted scintillation photons *N* in a single scintillation event can often be described by linear superposition of one or two exponential decays.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] where *τf* and *τs* are the fast (or prompt) and the slow (or delayed) decay constants.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Many scintillators are characterized by 2 time components: one fast (or prompt), the other slow (or delayed).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] While the fast component usually dominates, the relative amplitude *A* and *B* of the two components depend on the scintillating material.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Both of these components can also be a function of the energy loss *dE*/*dx*.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] In cases where this energy loss dependence is strong, the overall decay time constant varies with the type of incident particle.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Such scintillators enable pulse shape discrimination, i.e., particle identification based on the decay characteristics of the PMT electric pulse.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] For instance, when BaF2 is used, γ rays typically excite the fast component, while α particles excite the slow component: it is thus possible to identify them based on the decay time of the PMT signal.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Organic scintillators are aromatic hydrocarbon compounds which contain benzene ring structures interlinked in various ways.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Their luminescence typically decays within a few nanoseconds.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Some organic scintillators are pure crystals.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The most common types are anthracene (C 14H 10, decay time ≈30 ns), stilbene (C 14H 12, 4.5 ns decay time), and naphthalene (C 10H 8, few ns decay time).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] They are very durable, but their response is anisotropic (which spoils energy resolution when the source is not collimated), and they cannot be easily machined, nor can they be grown in large sizes; hence they are not very often used.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Anthracene has the highest light output of all organic scintillators and is therefore chosen as a reference: the light outputs of other scintillators are sometimes expressed as a percentage of anthracene light output.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] These are liquid solutions of one or more organic scintillators in an organic solvent.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The typical solutes are fluors such as *p*-terphenyl (C 18H 14), PBD (C 20H 14N 2O), butyl PBD (C 24H 22N 2O), PPO (C 15H 11NO), and wavelength shifter such as POPOP (C 24H 16N 2O).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The most widely used solvents are toluene, xylene, benzene, phenylcyclohexane, triethylbenzene, and decalin.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Newer approaches combine several solvents or load different metals to achieve identification of incident particles.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] For many liquids, dissolved oxygen can act as a quenching agent and lead to reduced light output, hence the necessity to seal the solution in an oxygen-free, airtight enclosure.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The term "plastic scintillator" typically refers to a scintillating material in which the primary fluorescent emitter, called a fluor, is suspended in the **base**, a solid polymer matrix.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] While this combination is typically accomplished through the dissolution of the fluor prior to bulk polymerization, the fluor is sometimes associated with the polymer directly, either covalently or through coordination, as is the case with many Li6 plastic scintillators.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Polyethylene naphthalate has been found to exhibit scintillation by itself without any additives and is expected to replace existing plastic scintillators due to higher performance and lower price.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Plastic scintillators are known to show light output saturation when the energy density is large (Birks' law).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The most common bases used in plastic scintillators are the aromatic plastics, polymers with aromatic rings as pendant groups along the polymer backbone, amongst which polyvinyltoluene (PVT) and polystyrene (PS) are the most prominent.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] While the base does fluoresce in the presence of ionizing radiation, its low yield and negligible transparency to its own emission make the use of fluors necessary in the construction of a practical scintillator.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Aside from the aromatic plastics, the most common base is polymethylmethacrylate (PMMA), which carries two advantages over many other bases: high ultraviolet and visible light transparency and mechanical properties and higher durability with respect to brittleness.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The lack of fluorescence associated with PMMA is often compensated through the addition of an aromatic co-solvent, usually naphthalene.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] A plastic scintillator based on PMMA in this way boasts transparency to its own radiation, helping to ensure uniform collection of light.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Other common bases include polyvinyl xylene (PVX) polymethyl, 2,4-dimethyl, 2,4,5-trimethyl styrenes, polyvinyl diphenyl, polyvinyl naphthalene, polyvinyl tetrahydronaphthalene, and copolymers of these and other bases.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Also known as luminophors, these compounds absorb the scintillation of the base and then emit at larger wavelength, effectively converting the ultraviolet radiation of the base into the more easily transferred visible light.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Further increasing the attenuation length can be accomplished through the addition of a second fluor, referred to as a spectrum shifter or converter, often resulting in the emission of blue or green light.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Inorganic scintillators are usually crystals grown in high temperature furnaces, for example, alkali metal halides, often with a small amount of activator impurity.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The most widely used is NaI(Tl) (thallium-doped sodium iodide); its scintillation light is blue.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Other inorganic alkali halide crystals are: CsI(Tl), CsI(Na), CsI(pure), CsF, KI(Tl), LiI(Eu).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Some non-alkali crystals include: BGO, BaF 2, CaF 2(Eu), ZnS(Ag), CaWO 4, CdWO 4, YAG(Ce) (Y 3Al 5O 12(Ce)), GSO, LSO, GAGG:Ce.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] (For more examples, see also phosphors).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Newly developed products include LaCl 3(Ce), lanthanum chloride doped with cerium, as well as a cerium-doped lanthanum bromide, LaBr 3(Ce).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] In addition LaBr3(Ce) offers a higher stopping power for γ rays (density of 5.08 g/cm3 versus 3.67 g/cm3 for NaI(Tl)).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] LYSO (Lu 1.8Y 0.2SiO 5(Ce)) has an even higher density (7.1 g/cm3, comparable to BGO), is non-hygroscopic, and has a higher light output than BGO (32 photons/keV γ), in addition to being rather fast (41 ns decay time versus 300 ns for BGO).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] A disadvantage of some inorganic crystals, e.g., NaI, is their hygroscopicity, a property which requires them to be housed in an airtight container to protect them from moisture.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] CsI(Tl) and BaF2 are only slightly hygroscopic and do not usually need protection.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] CsF, NaI(Tl), LaCl 3(Ce), LaBr 3(Ce) are hygroscopic, while BGO, CaF 2(Eu), LYSO, and YAG(Ce) are not.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Inorganic crystals can be cut to small sizes and arranged in an array configuration so as to provide position sensitivity.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Such arrays are often used in medical physics or security applications to detect X-rays or γ rays: high-*Z*, high density materials (e.g.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] LYSO, BGO) are typically preferred for this type of applications.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Scintillation in inorganic crystals is typically slower than in organic ones, ranging typically from 1.48 ns for ZnO(Ga) to 9000 ns for CaWO 4.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Exceptions are CsF (~5 ns), fast BaF 2 (0.7 ns; the slow component is at 630 ns), as well as the newer products (LaCl 3(Ce), 28 ns; LaBr 3(Ce), 16 ns; LYSO, 41 ns).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] For the imaging application, one of the advantage of inorganic crystals is very high light yield.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Some high light yield scintillators above 100,000 photons/MeV at 662 keV are very recently reported for LuI 3(Ce), SrI 2(Eu), and Cs 2HfCl 6.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Many semiconductor scintillator phosphors are known, such as ZnS(Ag) (mentioned in the history section), CdS(Ag), ZnO(Zn), ZnO(Ga), CdS(In), ZnSe(O), and ZnTe(O), but none of these are available as single crystals.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] CdS(Te) and ZnSe(Te) have been commercially available in single crystal form, but their luminosity is partially quenched at room temperature.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] GaAs(Si,B) is a recently discovered cryogenic semiconductor scintillator with high light output in the infra-red and apparently no afterglow.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] In combination with ultra-low noise cryogenic photodetectors it is the target in experiments to detect rare, low-energy electronic excitations from interacting dark matter.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Gaseous scintillators consist of nitrogen and the noble gases helium, argon, krypton, and xenon, with helium and xenon receiving the most attention.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The scintillation process is due to the de-excitation of single atoms excited by the passage of an incoming particle.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This de-excitation is very rapid (~1 ns), so the detector response is quite fast.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Coating the walls of the container with a wavelength shifter is generally necessary as those gases typically emit in the ultraviolet and PMTs respond better to the visible blue-green region.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] In nuclear physics, gaseous detectors have been used to detect fission fragments or heavy charged particles.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The most common glass scintillators are cerium-activated lithium or boron silicates.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Since both lithium and boron have large neutron cross-sections, glass detectors are particularly well suited to the detection of thermal (slow) neutrons.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Lithium is more widely used than boron since it has a greater energy release on capturing a neutron and therefore greater light output.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Glass scintillators are however sensitive to electrons and γ rays as well (pulse height discrimination can be used for particle identification).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Being very robust, they are also well-suited to harsh environmental conditions.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Their response time is ≈10 ns, their light output is however low, typically ≈30% of that of anthracene.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Birowosuto at al. studied the scintillation properties of 3-D and 2-D layered perovskites under X-ray excitation.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] MAPbBr3 (CH 3NH 3PbBr 3) emits at 550 nm and MAPbI3 (CH 3NH 3PbI 3) at 750 nm which is attributed to exciton emission near the band gap of the compounds.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] In this first generation of Pb-halide perovskites the emission is strongly quenched at room temperature and less than 1 000 ph/MeV survive.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] At 10 K however intense emission is observed and write about yields up to 200 000 ph/MeV.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The quenching is attributed to the small e-h binding energy in the exciton that decreases for Cl to Br to I .
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Interestingly one may replace the organic MA group with Cs+ to obtain full inorganic CsPbX3 halide perovskites.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Depending on the Cl, Br, I content the triplet X-ray excited exciton emission can be tuned from 430 nm to 700 nm .
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] One may also dilute Cs with Rb to obtain similar tuning.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Above very recent developments demonstrate that the organic-inorganic and all inorganic Pb-halide perovskites have various interesting scintillation properties.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] More recently, a new material class first reported by Professor Biwu Ma's research group, called 0D organic metal halide hybrid (OMHH), an extension of the perovskite materials.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This class of materials exhibits strong exciton binding of hundreds of meV, resulting in their high photoluminescent quantum efficiency of almost unity.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Their large stoke shift and reabsorption-free properties make them desirable.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Their potential applications for scintillators have been reported by the same group, and others.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] In 2020,(C38H34P2)MnBr4 was reported to have a light yield up to 80 000 Photon/MeV despite its low Z compared to traditional all inorganic.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Impressive light yields from other 0D OMHH have been reported.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] There is a great potential to realize new generation scintillators from this material class.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] However, they are limited by their relatively long response time in microseconds, which is an area of intense research.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Transitions made by the free valence electrons of the molecules are responsible for the production of scintillation light in organic crystals.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] These electrons are associated with the whole molecule rather than any particular atom and occupy the so-called -molecular orbitals.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The ground state S0 is a singlet state above which are the excited singlet states (S*, S**, ...), the lowest triplet state (T0), and its excited levels (T*, T**, ...).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] A fine structure corresponding to molecular vibrational modes is associated with each of those electron levels.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The energy spacing between electron levels is ≈1 eV; the spacing between the vibrational levels is about 1/10 of that for electron levels.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] An incoming particle can excite either an electron level or a vibrational level.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The singlet excitations immediately decay (< 10 ps) to the S* state without the emission of radiation (internal degradation).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The S* state then decays to the ground state S0 (typically to one of the vibrational levels above S0) by emitting a scintillation photon.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This is the prompt component or fluorescence.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The transparency of the scintillator to the emitted photon is due to the fact that the energy of the photon is less than that required for an S0 → S* transition (the transition is usually being to a vibrational level above S0).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] When one of the triplet states gets excited, it immediately decays to the T0 state with no emission of radiation (internal degradation).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] and leaves one of the molecules in the S* state, which then decays to S0 with the release of a scintillation photon.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Since the T0-T0 interaction takes time, the scintillation light is delayed: this is the slow or delayed component (corresponding to delayed fluorescence).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Sometimes, a direct T0 → S0 transition occurs (also delayed), and corresponds to the phenomenon of phosphorescence.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Note that the observational difference between delayed-fluorescence and phosphorescence is the difference in the wavelengths of the emitted optical photon in an S* → S0 transition versus a T0 → S0 transition.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Organic scintillators can be dissolved in an organic solvent to form either a liquid or plastic scintillator.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The scintillation process is the same as described for organic crystals (above); what differs is the mechanism of energy absorption: energy is first absorbed by the solvent, then passed onto the scintillation solute (the details of the transfer are not clearly understood).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The scintillation process in inorganic materials is due to the electronic band structure found in crystals and is not molecular in nature as is the case with organic scintillators.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] An incoming particle can excite an electron from the valence band to either the conduction band or the exciton band (located just below the conduction band and separated from the valence band by an energy gap; see picture).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This leaves an associated hole behind, in the valence band.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Impurities create electronic levels in the forbidden gap.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The excitons are loosely bound electron-hole pairs which wander through the crystal lattice until they are captured as a whole by impurity centers.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The latter then rapidly de-excite by emitting scintillation light (fast component).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The activator impurities are typically chosen so that the emitted light is in the visible range or near-UV where photomultipliers are effective.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The holes associated with electrons in the conduction band are independent from the latter.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Those holes and electrons are captured successively by impurity centers exciting certain metastable states not accessible to the excitons.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The delayed de-excitation of those metastable impurity states again results in scintillation light (slow component).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] BGO (bismuth germanium oxide) is a pure inorganic scintillator without any activator impurity.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] There, the scintillation process is due to an optical transition of the Bi3+ ion, a major constituent of the crystal.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] In tungstate scintillators CaWO 4 and CdWO 4 the emission is due to radiative decay of self-trapped excitons.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The scintillation process in GaAs doped with silicon and boron impurities is different from conventional scintillators in that the silicon *n*-type doping provides a built-in population of delocalized electrons at the bottom of the conduction band.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Some of the boron impurity atoms reside on arsenic sites and serve as acceptors.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] A scintillation photon is produced whenever an acceptor atom such as boron captures an ionization hole from the valence band and that hole recombines radiatively with one of the delocalized electrons.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Unlike many other semiconductors, the delocalized electrons provided by the silicon are not "frozen out" at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Above the Mott transition concentration of 8×1015 free carriers per cm3, the "metallic" state is maintained at cryogenic temperatures because mutual repulsion drives any additional electrons into the next higher available energy level, which is in the conduction band.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The spectrum of photons from this process is centered at 930 nm (1.33 eV) and there are three other emission bands centered at 860, 1070, and 1335 nm from other minor processes.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Each of these emission bands has a different luminosity and decay time.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The high scintillation luminosity is surprising because (1) with a refractive index of about 3.5, escape is inhibited by total internal reflection and (2) experiments at 90K report narrow-beam infrared absorption coefficients of several per cm.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] This cross section is about 107 times larger than Thomson scattering but comparable to the optical cross section of the conduction electrons in a metal mirror.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] In gases, the scintillation process is due to the de-excitation of single atoms excited by the passage of an incoming particle (a very rapid process: ≈1 ns).
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Strong non-linearities are observed in the detector response especially at lower energies.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The reduction in light output is stronger for organics than for inorganic crystals.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Therefore, where needed, inorganic crystals, e.g.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] CsI(Tl), ZnS(Ag) (typically used in thin sheets as α-particle monitors), CaF 2(Eu), should be preferred to organic materials.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Typical applications are α-survey instruments, dosimetry instruments, and heavy ion *dE*/*dx* detectors.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Gaseous scintillators have also been used in nuclear physics experiments.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The detection efficiency for electrons is essentially 100% for most scintillators.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] But because electrons can make large angle scatterings (sometimes backscatterings), they can exit the detector without depositing their full energy in it.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The back-scattering is a rapidly increasing function of the atomic number *Z* of the scintillator material.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Organic scintillators, having a lower *Z* than inorganic crystals, are therefore best suited for the detection of low-energy (< 10 MeV) beta particles.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The situation is different for high energy electrons: since they mostly lose their energy by bremsstrahlung at the higher energies, a higher-*Z* material is better suited for the detection of the bremsstrahlung photon and the production of the electromagnetic shower which it can induce.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] High-*Z* materials, e.g. inorganic crystals, are best suited for the detection of gamma rays.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The three basic ways that a gamma ray interacts with matter are: the photoelectric effect, Compton scattering, and pair production.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The photon is completely absorbed in photoelectric effect and pair production, while only partial energy is deposited in any given Compton scattering.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The cross section for the photoelectric process is proportional to *Z*5, that for pair production proportional to *Z*2, whereas Compton scattering goes roughly as *Z*.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] A high-*Z* material therefore favors the former two processes, enabling the detection of the full energy of the gamma ray.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] If the gamma rays are at higher energies (>5 MeV), pair production dominates.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Since the neutron is not charged it does not interact via the Coulomb force and therefore does not ionize the scintillation material.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] It must first transfer some or all of its energy via the strong force to a charged atomic nucleus.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] The positively charged nucleus then produces ionization.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Fast neutrons (generally >0.5 MeV ) primarily rely on the recoil proton in (n,p) reactions; materials rich in hydrogen, e.g. plastic scintillators, are therefore best suited for their detection.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Slow neutrons rely on nuclear reactions such as the (n,γ) or (n,α) reactions, to produce ionization.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Their mean free path is therefore quite large unless the scintillator material contains nuclides having a high cross section for these nuclear reactions such as 6Li or 10B.
[src:pet-imaging/scintillator] Materials such as LiI(Eu) or glass silicates are therefore particularly well-suited for the detection of slow (thermal) neutrons.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] The technique needs delivery of a gamma-emitting radioisotope (a radionuclide) into the patient, normally through injection into the bloodstream.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] On occasion, the radioisotope is a simple soluble dissolved ion, such as an isotope of gallium(III).
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Usually, however, a marker radioisotope is attached to a specific ligand to create a radioligand, whose properties bind it to certain types of tissues.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] This marriage allows the combination of ligand and radiopharmaceutical to be carried and bound to a place of interest in the body, where the ligand concentration is seen by a gamma camera.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] SPECT and other nuclear medicine imaging technologies differ from radiography by imaging the amount of biological activity rather than the structure of the body.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] This is measured by detecting photon emissions from decaying radionuclides and then reconstructed into a 3-D image.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] These radionucleotides are bonded to carrier molecules that localize the function of interest.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] SPECT imaging is performed by using a gamma camera to acquire multiple 2-D images (also called projections), from multiple angles.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] A computer is then used to apply a tomographic reconstruction algorithm to the multiple projections, yielding a 3-D data set.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] This data set may then be manipulated to show thin slices along any chosen axis of the body, similar to those obtained from other tomographic techniques, such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), X-ray computed tomography (X-ray CT), and positron emission tomography (PET).
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] SPECT is similar to PET in its use of radioactive tracer material and detection of gamma rays.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] In contrast with PET, the tracers used in SPECT emit gamma radiation that is measured directly, whereas PET measures two gamma rays created from the annihilation of positrons that travel in opposing directions.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] A PET scanner detects these emissions "coincident" in time, which allows for more precise collimation which results in higher spatial resolution and higher quality images than SPECT.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] PET resolution typically lies within 0.5–6 mm for the more modern PET systems and around 1 cm for SPECT systems.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Partly from this, SPECT scanners are cheaper than PET scans because of the more durable and plentiful radioisotopes that are used, such as technetium-99m.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Because SPECT acquisition is very similar to planar gamma camera imaging, the same radiopharmaceuticals may be used.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] To acquire SPECT images, the gamma camera is rotated around the patient.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Projections are acquired at defined points during the rotation, typically every 3–6 degrees.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] 180-degree and 360-degree are standard rotation arcs depending on what is being imaged in the patient.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] The time taken to obtain each projection is also variable, but 15–20 seconds is typical.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] This gives a total scan time of 15–20 minutes.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Multi-headed gamma cameras can accelerate acquisition.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] For example, a dual-headed camera can be used with heads spaced 180 degrees apart, allowing two projections to be acquired simultaneously, with each head requiring 180 degrees of rotation.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Triple-head cameras with 120-degree spacing are also used.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Cardiac gated acquisitions are possible with SPECT, just as with planar imaging techniques such as multi gated acquisition scan (MUGA).
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] SPECT can be used to complement any gamma imaging study, where a true 3D representation can be helpful, such as tumor imaging, infection (leukocyte) imaging, thyroid imaging or bone scintigraphy.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Because SPECT permits accurate localization in 3D space, it can be used to provide information about localized function in internal organs, such as functional cardiac or brain imaging.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Myocardial perfusion imaging (MPI) is a form of functional cardiac imaging, used for the diagnosis of ischemic heart disease.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] The underlying principle is that under conditions of stress, diseased myocardium receives less blood flow than normal myocardium.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] MPI is one of several types of cardiac stress test.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] A cardiac specific radiopharmaceutical is administered, e.g., 99mTc-tetrofosmin (Myoview, GE healthcare), 99mTc-sestamibi (Cardiolite, Bristol-Myers Squibb) or Thallium-201 chloride.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Following this, the heart rate is raised to induce myocardial stress, either by exercise on a treadmill or pharmacologically with adenosine, dobutamine, or dipyridamole (aminophylline can be used to reverse the effects of dipyridamole).
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] SPECT imaging performed after stress reveals the distribution of the radiopharmaceutical, and therefore the relative blood flow to the different regions of the myocardium.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Diagnosis is made by comparing stress images to a further set of images obtained at rest which are normally acquired prior to the stress images.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] MPI has been demonstrated to have an overall accuracy of about 83% (sensitivity: 85%; specificity: 72%) (in a review, not exclusively of SPECT MPI), and is comparable with (or better than) other non-invasive tests for ischemic heart disease.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Usually, the gamma-emitting tracer used in functional brain imaging is technetium (99mTc) exametazime.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] 99mTc, which has a six-hour half-life, is a metastable nuclear isomer that emits gamma rays detectable by a gamma camera.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Attaching it to exametazime allows it to be taken up by brain tissue in a manner proportional to brain blood flow, in turn allowing cerebral blood flow to be assessed with the nuclear gamma camera.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Because blood flow in the brain is tightly coupled to local brain metabolism and energy use, the 99mTc-exametazime tracer (as well as the similar 99mTc-EC tracer) is used to assess brain metabolism regionally, in an attempt to diagnose and differentiate potential causal pathologies of dementia.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Meta-analysis of many reported studies suggests that SPECT with this tracer is about 74% sensitive at diagnosing Alzheimer's disease versus 81% sensitivity for clinical examination (such as cognitive testing).
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] More recent studies have shown the accuracy of SPECT in Alzheimer's diagnosis may be as high as 88%.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] In meta-analysis, SPECT was superior to clinical examination and clinical criteria (91% vs.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] 70%) in its ability to differentiate Alzheimer's disease from vascular dementias.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] This latter ability relates to SPECT's imaging of local metabolism of the brain, in which the patchy loss of cortical metabolism seen in multiple strokes differs clearly from the more even or "smooth" loss of non-occipital cortical brain function typical of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] 99mTc-exametazime SPECT scanning competes with fludeoxyglucose (FDG) PET scanning of the brain, which works to assess regional brain glucose metabolism, to provide very similar information about local brain damage from many processes.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] SPECT is more widely available, because the radioisotope used is longer-lasting and far less expensive in SPECT, and the gamma-scanning equipment is less expensive as well.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] In the nuclear power sector, the SPECT technique can be applied to image radioisotope distributions in irradiated nuclear fuels.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Due to the irradiation of nuclear fuel (e.g. uranium) with neutrons in a nuclear reactor, a wide array of gamma-emitting radionuclides are naturally produced in the fuel, such as fission products (cesium-137, barium-140 and europium-154) and activation products (chromium-51 and cobalt-58).
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] These may be imaged using SPECT in order to verify the presence of fuel rods in a stored fuel assembly for IAEA safeguards purposes, to validate predictions of core simulation codes, or to study the behavior of the nuclear fuel in normal operation, or in accident scenarios.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] In SPECT, the quality of reconstructed images is generally limited by low spatial resolution and sensitivity, which causes increased attenuation and the risk of artifacts due to its limitations.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Scanning is time consuming, and it is essential that there is no patient movement during the scan time.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] This is due to the detector rotation around the patient that collects multiple projections.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Movement can cause major imperfections to the reconstructed images, although movement compensation reconstruction techniques can help with this.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Furthermore, iterative algorithms can be made more efficacious using the superiorization methodology.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Older versions of SPECT technology used of MLEM algorithms or maximum likelihood expectation maximization algorithms.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Moving forward to more modern day systems, the algorithms have improved to algorithms such as OSEM or the Ordered Subset Expectation Maximization algorithm.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] These algorithms are like MLEM but break the data down into subsets, which creates faster and higher quality image reconstruction.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] These algorithms allow for SPECT systems to limit the amount of artifacts and attenuation that appear in images.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] By doing so, the activity of the radiation in tissues can be more accurately interpreted.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] Along with OSEM, scatter correction and resolution recovery algorithms are also applied to further clear up SPECT images.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] In some cases, a SPECT gamma scanner may be modified to operate with a conventional CT scanner to combine Single-photon emission computed tomography with Computed tomography to provide both the detailed physiology of the body, as well as the ability to show the structure of the body being scanned.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] By layering the SPECT and CT data, a more accurate image can be created.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] In addition to this, the addition of CT helps to correct attenuation in the SPECT imaging.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] This can be useful for identifying tumors or tissues that may be seen on SPECT scintigraphy but are difficult to locate precisely with regard to other anatomical structures.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] In more recent versions of SPECT/CT systems, the detectors have improved significantly through the use of cadmium-zinc-telluride (CZT) detectors and the advancements in reconstruction algorithms.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] These advancements have increased image quality compared to older versions.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] With the advancements of SPECT/CT, the technology is playing an increasing role in clinical imaging applications and theranostics.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] For example, SPECT/CT may be used in sestamibi parathyroid scan applications, where the technique is useful in locating ectopic parathyroid adenomas, which may not be in their usual locations in the thyroid gland.
[src:pet-imaging/single-photon-emission-computed-tomography] The overall performance of SPECT systems can be performed by quality control tools such as the Jaszczak phantom.
